Yes, there is a function in React called `useCallback`. It's a Hook that allows you to memoize a function so that it's not recreated on every render.

Here's an example of how you might use `useCallback`:

```jsx
import { useCallback } from 'react';

function MyComponent({ onClick }) {
  const handleClick = useCallback(() => {
    console.log('Button clicked!');
    onClick();
  }, [onClick]);

  return (
    <button onClick={handleClick}>
      Click me!
    </button>
  );
}
```

In this example, the `handleClick` function is memoized so that it's only recreated when the `onClick` prop changes.

However, if you don't need to pass the function as a prop to another component, you can use the `useCallback` Hook without the dependency array.

```jsx
import { useCallback } from 'react';

function MyComponent() {
  const handleClick = useCallback(() => {
    console.log('Button clicked!');
  }, []);

  return (
    <button onClick={handleClick}>
      Click me!
    </button>
  );
}
```

In this case, the `handleClick` function will be recreated on every render.

